description:
Shepherd's Purse (Capsella bursa-pastoris)

2 April 2016
Greenbelt Corridor Ray Roberts/Lewisville Lake FM 428 Access Area, Aubrey Branch
Denton County, Texas

Shepherd's Purse is an introduced species to North America and the Western Hemisphere including Greenland, as indicated by the Plants Database of the United States Department of Agriculture. 

Mountain Rose Herbs reports the following: "Shepherd's purse is a temperate zone weed in the mustard family, the same as cabbage, broccoli, and watercress. It is a biennial with an erect stem emerging from a rosette of leaves at its base. It bears four-petalled white flowers that produce heart or purse shaped seedpods. Its name comes from its resemblance to a shepherd's pouch in the middle ages. All of the aboveground parts of the plant are used in herbal medicines."

Shepherd's Purse has various medicinal or herbal uses and some of these have been used since antiquity, or so read the claims online. It is also edible as a green and may be added to one's diet and certain birds including domestic chickens appear to favor it when available. Here's a brief quote from Sand Mountain Herbs: "Shepherds purse is one of the earliest greens in early spring. As a pot herb, the leaves are best eaten before the flower stalks appear. Some people consider it to have a bite to its taste much like a radish, but I really don't see it being even that hot. It is very mild in my opinion. It is uncharacteristically mild for a mustard green when it is young and tender. It is also very good to add to salads, stews, soups, and sauces. A lot of birds love Shepherd's purse. Chickens will devour the whole plant like there is no tomorrow. In fact, it will cause the yolk to change color and have a stronger taste when the chickens eat it. Grouse's, chaffinches, and gold finchs also like to eat the seeds." 

Here are many additional common names by which this wildflower is recognized by way of Mountain Rose Herbs: "shepherd's heart, shepherd's bog, shepherd’s bag, shepherd’s scrip, shepherd’s sprout, coco wort or cocowort, mother's heart, case weed, case wort or casewort, pickpocket or pick pocket, toywort or toy wort, blindweed or blind weed, pepper and salt, rattle pouches, rattleweed or rattle weed, Chinese Cress, Nazuna, pick purse, permacety, toywort or toy wort, St. James' weed or St. James wort, St. Anthony's fire, pepper grass or peppergrass, witch's pocket, witch’s pouches, lady’s purse, ladies purse, poor man’s parmacettie, bourse de pasteur, hirtentasche, hirtenfaschel, Borsa de Pastor, clappedepouch, and Borsa di pastore."

Sources:

"Capsella bursa-pastoris (L.) Medik. - Shepherd's Purse," Plants Database, United States Department of Agriculture, National Resources Conservation Service, photographs, range map, description, classification, resources, accessed 4.4.16, http://plants.usda.gov/core/profile?symbol=cabu2

"Shepherd's Purse Benefits," Sand Mountain Herbs, long description, accessed 4.4.16, http://www.sandmountainherbs.com/articles/shepherds-purse-benefits.html

"Shepherd's Purse Extract," Mountain Rose Herbs, description, accessed 4.4.16, https://www.mountainroseherbs.com/products/shepherds-purse-extract/profile

This plant was rather interesting. I don't recall seeing this one before this year. This plant had a bunch of these little heart shaped clubs on it. The leave made a rounded shape and gave the plant some curvature. They also had some white buds on them or some kind of flower. They are in some areas of Lake Arlington down by the dam section of the lake; well the park closest to the old yacht club site that isn't there anymore. I have found some by the wooden fence and the wall of the fancy mansion near the lake. This plant is rather interesting and stands only about five or six inches at some points I think my measurements maybe off. The hearts have a little vein that runs vertically in the middle of the leaf. It is a very interesting plant. Lake Arlington has been the only place I have seen this particular plant.

Before I went to meet with the Rockwall Open Space Alliance, I stopped by a few parks in Rockwall. This one, Harry Myers Park, is exceptional! There is quite a bit of wildlife habitat, and, because of that, lots of critters! Looking forward to coming back here in spring.

description: This aquatic plant was growing at the edge of the streambed that permeates the village

Capsella bursa-pastoris starts in the kingdom Plantae, which includes mainly multicellular, predominantly photosynthetic eukaryotes. The Phylum Tracheophyta, comprising of plants with a vascular system including ferns and fern allies as well as seed plants. The class Magnoliopsida, Class consisting of roughly 170,000 species of angiosperms. The order Brassicales, includes cabbages and capers, as well as mignonette, mustard, and nasturtiums. Brassicales includes 17 families, 398 genera, and 4,450 species. The family  Brassicaceae or Cruciferae, (commonly known as the Mustard family) The family consists mostly of herbaceous plants with annual, biennial, or perennial lifespans having four, free saccate, sepals and four clawed free petals. The plants in this family are angiosperms, which usually are herbaceous plants. These plants bear flowers with four sepals and four petals that resemble a cross, giving it its former name, Cruciferae. These petals are usually white, yellow, red or blueish-purple. The fruit of the species in this family are called silicles or siliques. The leaves are usually alternate but sometimes opposite as well as sometimes being in basal rosettes. In the genus Capsella, they are known for being a self fertilizing plant with white petals. They have silicle fruits that are strongly obcompressed, and seeds that are mucilaginous when wet. The species bursa-pastoris is described as having a simple stem, a rosette of lobed leaves at the base and upper leaves being sessile. As well as the silique fruits being triangular to heart shaped. This species is comparable to all other species in its family but it does have some key differences. Such as this plant has white petals that are clumped together to whereas Chorispora tenella has purple petals that are more clawed and spread out. As well as having sinuate-dentate leaves; fruits that are silique terete and form long, tapered beaks; and having seeds that are uniseriate. Unlike most flowering plants, it flowers almost all year round. Like many other annual ruderals exploiting disturbed ground, Capsella bursa-pastoris reproduces entirely from seed, has a long soil seed bank, and short generation time and is capable of producing several generations each year.
This plant was collected on a grassy land scape in a pasture. It was surrounded by orchard grass and other species of mustard plant. The soil it was in was weathered basalt that was moist and exposed to full sunlight. This specific plant lacked in variation besides silicles being smaller in size than the key states, they were about 3mm when they key said them to be 5mm. This may have been caused due to a lack in shade and competition of nutrients.

description:
Kokoška pastuší tobolka (Capsella bursa-pastoris) je jednoletá až dvouletá bylina. Patří do čeledi křížatých neboli brukvovitých. Je vysoká 20 až 40 cm, ale může být i vyšší. Patří mezi léčivé rostliny– zastavuje krvácení. Dnes se jedná o obecný plevel. Znehodnocuje především pícniny.
PopisEditovat

Kokoška pastuší tobolka je velmi proměnlivou nenápadnou rostlinou. Může být vysoká až půl metru. Často má větvenou lodyhu. Má přízemní listovou růžici, kterou tvoří chobotnatě laločnaté až peřenosečné, vzácně i nedělené listy. V horní části lodyhy se nachází celokrajné, objímavé, kopinaté listy se střelovitou bází.

Všechny listy jsou chlupaté.[1]

Květy jsou drobné, bílé. Někdy jsou bezkorunné. Mohou být až 5 mm široké. Tvoří koncový hrozen. Klínovitě obvejčité, nekřídlaté šešulky jsou vícesemenné, trojúhelníkovité či podlouhle klínovité.[1][2][3]

VýskytEditovat

S touto bylinou se můžeme setkat na rumištích, polích, zahradách, okrajích cest, úhorech, dlažbách, hřištích atd.

Nalezneme ji v nížinách i v horských oblastech.[3]Ve vyšších polohách se s ní setkáme spíše roztroušeně a spíše v oblastech osídlených lidmi.[1]

Dokáže vyrůst i v půdách sešlapávaných a jinak zraňovaných. Snese půdy jílovité, písčité, humózní, štěrkovité, minerální. atd.[1]

RozšířeníEditovat

Tato bylina roste téměř po celém světě.[1] Často doprovází kulturní rostliny.[2] Původně byla rozšířena jen ve Středomoří a Malé Asii.[1]

Doba květuEditovat

Doba květu této byliny je neobyčejně dlouhá. Kvete od února do října. Při teplých zimách si dokáže udržet květy po celý rok.[2]

ObecněEditovat

Jedná se o léčivku. Dokáže zastavit krvácení. Mírně snižuje krevní tlak. Sbírá se kvetoucí nať po celou dobu vegetace. Může se užívat vnitřně – při krvácení z nosu, děložním či silném menstruačním krvácení, při onemocněních močových orgánů atd. Dále ji můžeme upotřebit při vnějších poraněních, jako jsou rány, otoky, pohmožděniny, záněty šlach, vyrážky či při neurovegetativních obtížích v pubertě a v klimaktériu.[4]

Obsahuje tyramin, histamin, dusík, betain, cholin a jeho ester acetylcholin, saponiny, sirné látky, třísloviny, flavonový glykosid diosmin a větší množství minerálních látek.[1] Semena této rostliny lze použít místo tymiánu či hořčice.[5

Fruits are triangular or obcordate in shape.
